{
  "doc_id": "51070",
  "text": "Our ultimate goal is to develop a general literature search engine covering a broad range of biomedical datasets. This study takes the initial step to validate the feasibility of automatic extraction of dataset mentions from literature and search relevant datasets based on extracted metadata information of datasets. Specifically, we take GWAS datasets as a use case. Targeting the associations between genetic polymorphisms and human phenotypes/traits (e.g., diseases), GWAS has a wide range of biomedical applications (e.g., targeted drug and diagnostics development [CITATION_1] ) and an exponential increase of related publications in recent years. [CITATION_2] Moreover, the unified case-control study design [CITATION_3] makes it a typical and general use case for the initial exploration of our study. The datasets used for GWAS usually contain populationlevel phenotype information, and the experimental results output from GWAS usually contain genotype-phenotype associations (i.e., SNP-traits associations). [CITATION_4] However, current data repositories such as GWAS Catalog [CITATION_5] mainly focus on providing search functions for traits and study results (i.e., SNPs, p-value) extracted from published GWAS papers, instead of information about the original cohort datasets used in study. [CITATION_6] Moreover, although GWAS Catalog incorporates automatic trait and SNP extraction into the curation pipeline, it still relies on manual curation by domain experts, which is time-consuming and labor-intensive. Pilot works of linking literature with genomic-level information, such as the GWAS Integrator [CITATION_7] and Phenotype-Genotype Integrator (PheGenI) [CITATION_8] , are also built upon the manually curated GWAS Catalog.",
